communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[ProMED-mail recently posted reports of the mumps outbreak that started on the Ohio State University (OSU) campus in the city of Columbus, Ohio and then spread into the surrounding counties (Delaware, Franklin, Fairfield, Licking, and Union) in central Ohio, but also involved Hamilton County in the south western portion of the state, in which the city of Cincinnati is located. As of the last previous post (4 Apr 2014) the total number of cases was 129. Now there are 153 cases, with 3 additional counties involved (Athens in south eastern, Belmont in eastern, and Pickaway in central Ohio), although most cases continue to be in Franklin County in which the city of Columbus and OSU are located.

The mumps vaccine is administered as part of a combination vaccine that provides protection against measles, mumps, and rubella (MMR) (http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/PDF/rr/rr4708.pdf). The MMR vaccine in the United States is given in 2 doses: the 1st dose is given at 12-15 months of age and the 2nd dose before entering school, at 4-6 years of age (http://www.vaccines.gov/diseases/mumps/index.html). The American College Health Association has recommended that colleges and universities require that students have documented receipt of 2 doses of MMR vaccine or have other acceptable evidence of measles, rubella, and mumps immunity before college enrolment (http://www.acha.org/topics/docs/CDC_ACHA_Mumps_Recommendations_Jul13.pdf). However, the news report above says that OSU does not mandate immunization against mumps before matriculation. Nevertheless, mumps outbreaks among vaccinated populations have been reported frequently during recent years, especially among college students where the intensity of exposure among students was presumed to have overcome the vaccine-induced immunity (http://wwwnc.cdc.gov/eid/article/20/4/13-1681_article.htm). Perhaps waning post-vaccination immunity and antigenic differences between outbreak strains and the vaccine viruses are additional explanations for mumps outbreaks in highly vaccinated populations (http://cid.oxfordjournals.org/content/47/11/1458.full).

CDC has evaluated use of a 3rd dose of MMR vaccine for mumps outbreak control during 2 previous mumps outbreaks in which transmission was sustained, despite high 2-dose coverage (http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/mm6148a2.htm). During both outbreaks, targeted vaccination was followed by a decrease in mumps incidence among the target group.

Columbus is the capital of and the largest city in the US state of Ohio. For a map of Ohio that shows the location of this state's counties, see http://geology.com/county-map/ohio.shtml.

Ohio State University (OSU) is a large public research university in Columbus, Ohio, with about 28 000 undergraduates and more than 35 on-campus residence halls, with additional separate housing for graduate and professional students, plus multiple extra-curricular organizations where social mixing can occur to facilitate spread of the disease (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ohio_State_University). - Mod.ML

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2391429,237.]
